== Overview ==
According to widely circulated genealogies, the Watarai clan traces its origins to {{ill|Ame-no-Oshikumone|ja|天押雲根命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Oshikumone|qq=}}, and they are considered descendants of the {{ill|Ise no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|伊勢国造|1=Ise no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise no Kuni no Miyatsuko|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}}<ref name="shinto">[[Nishikawa Junto]] (ed.), "Watarai Shrine Priest Genealogical Record," in *Shintō Taikei: Ronsetsu-hen, Vol. 7 (Ise Shintō, Part 2)*, Shintō Taikei Compilation Society, 1982, pp. 415–417.</ref>. Another theory suggests that the Watarai clan came to Ise with [[Toyouke Ōmikami]], the deity enshrined at the Gekū, originally from [[:en:Tango Province|Tango Province]]<ref>Ikegaki Miyuki, "The Enshrinement and Traditions of Toyōke Daijingū," *The Formation and Historical Significance of the Nihon Shoki*, Nenshōsha, 2022, pp. 317–319. (Original article: *Koten to Rekishi*, No. 1, 2018).</ref>. 

The clan served as hereditary priests (negi) of the Gekū from ancient times. During the late [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]] and [[:en:Nanboku-chō period|Nanboku-chō period]], they challenged the [[Ise Grand Shrine|Naikū]] (Inner Shrine) and advocated [[Ise faith|Ise Shintō]]. While the clan divided into numerous branches, only six families, including the Higaki and Matsuki families, retained the privilege of serving as negi.

